</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
KEEPING HEALTHY: TABLETS MAY BE ONE WAY TO COUNTERACT JET LAG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. KARL NEUMANN, Neumann is a Forest Hills, N.Y., pediatrician who writes 
on travel-related matters. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Anti Jet Lag Formula is a vitamin-amino acid formulation that the 
manufacturer claims can reduce the effects of jet lag. It contains two amino 
acids -- tryptophane to help induce sleep, and tyrosine to promote better 
performance during the day -- and vitamin B6 to help metabolize the 
tryptophane. Tablets are to be taken over a 12-hour period after arrival at 
your destination. 
</P>
<P>
Does it work? The accompanying literature gives testimonials from known 
personalities, but is weak on scientific facts to support claims. But 
dietitians say the ingredients can't harm you. The Anti Jet Lag Formula is 
available at drugstores, airports and from American Biosearch, 5820 Oberlin 
Drive, Suite 202, San Diego, Calif. 92121. A two-day supply is $5.95; for 12 
days, $24.95. 
</P>
<P>
Check with your physician if you take blood pressure medication and plan to 
travel to the tropics or to high-altitude destinations, says the Medical 
Travelers' Advisory. 
</P>
<P>
At high altitudes, getting sufficient oxygen depends on a more rapid heart 
rate. However, some blood pressure medication -- beta blockers, for example -- 
interferes with your heart beating faster. Therefore, your dosage of medication 
may have to be reduced before your trip. 
</P>
<P>
Diuretics (water pills) can cause problems when you travel from winter 
temperatures to the tropics. The combination of diuretics and increased 
perspiration may cause dehydration. The situation is further complicated by 
sports, exercise and, sometimes, the inability to get a low-salt diet. 
</P>
<P>
Brightly colored, lead-glazed earthen pottery items brought back from Mexico, 
China and other developing countries make attractive ornaments for your home. 
But think twice before using them for holding food, says the University of 
California, Berkeley, Wellness Letter. 
</P>
<P>
The problem is that these items may not have been fired at sufficiently high 
temperatures to bind the lead properly. As a result, foods, especially acidic 
foods such as wine, orange and tomato juices, coffee, some sauces, pickles and 
salad dressings can leach out the lead. Then when you eat the food, you absorb 
the lead, which could cause lead poisoning. 
</P>
<P>
Earthen pottery bought in Europe and Japan, where laws require that high 
temperatures be used, is less likely to cause problems. But even there, buy 
earthen jars from reputable dealers. 
</P>
<P>
If you must smoke when visiting developing countries, take cigarettes with you. 
The cigarettes you buy there may be more hazardous than those in this country. 
</P>
<P>
According to the World Health Organization, the worst cigarettes are in 
Indonesia. The average cigarette there contains about five times the tar and 
three times the nicotine of the average cigarette in North America and Western 
Europe. Other countries with particularly unhealthy cigarettes: Turkey and the 
Philippines. 
</P>
<P>
The best time to travel during pregnancy is the fourth through the sixth 
months, when you have adjusted to the pregnancy but are not yet so bulky that 
moving about is difficult. That's according to the booklet "Travel During 
Pregnancy." 
</P>
<P>
The safest seat belt during pregnancy is one with both shoulder and lap 
restraints. Fasten the lap belt low across the hips, under the bulge of your 
abdomen. Place a scarf or thin blanket between the belt and your body for 
increased comfort. 
</P>
<P>
Pregnant women take longer to adjust to jet lag, so allow a couple of days of 
rest after flights. 
</P>
<P>
For copies of the free booklet, write to the American College of Obstetricians 
and Gynecologists, 600 Maryland Ave. SW, Suite 300, Washington, D.C. 
20024-2588. 
</P>
<P>
Never sleep during the descent of airplane flights. Sleep decreases swallowing 
and swallowing helps you keep up with pressure changes during descent, 
according to the leaflet "Ears, Altitude and Airplane Travel." 
</P>
<P>
Use nasal sprays and decongestants after flights when ears do not unblock. If 
ear discomfort continues for more than a day, see a physician. Prolonged 
blockage in your ears can cause problems later. 
</P>
<P>
The free leaflet has many other helpful facts. Write to the American Academy of 
Otolaryngology, 1101 Vermont Ave. NW, Suite 302, Washington D.C. 20005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
