<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a boost to the Seabrook nuclear power plant, a federal bankruptcy judge in 
Manchester, N.H., refused to block low-power testing of the reactor and 
approved a settlement that ensures funding until the end of the year. "It is 
likely that Seabrook is ultimately going to go into commercial operation," said 
Judge James Yacos in a reorganization hearing of the Public Service Co. of New 
Hampshire, Seabrook's lead owner. Judge Yacos approved an agreement reached 
Thursday by state officials, Public Service and its creditors ensuring that New 
Hampshire ratepayers will not be charged for cleaning up Seabrook if it 
conducts the atomic tests but does not operate commercially. Before the 
agreement was reached, state officials had asked Yacos to delay the tests until 
commercial operation is assured. 
</P>
