<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Students at the University of New Mexico in Albuquerque and Wayne State 
University in Detroit continued sit-ins. UNM President Gerald May, whose outer 
office has been held since Tuesday, said regents would soon reconsider a 
$50-a-semester tuition hike to $686. About 40 protesters said they would 
continue the sit-in but promised to tidy May's office, which has become 
cluttered during the protest. In Detroit, about 70 black students who have 
occupied the Wayne State student center since Wednesday said they will discuss 
with administrators Monday demands for stepped-up minority student and faculty 
recruitment and a requirement that each instructor teach an African-related 
course. 
</P>
